Rationale: Sepsis-related deaths declined from 2000 to 2019, but mortality rates have recently increased from 277 per 100,000 people age 65 and over in 2019 to 331 per 100,000 in the same age group [1]. Sepsis mortality rates decreased from 1991 to 2000 but then increased from 26.6% in 2001–2005 to 29.2% in 2006–2009 [2]. Based on this information, the claim that sepsis rates have been decreasing REFUTES the evidence provided.
